    {# ══ EXAM TRAPS ══ #}
    <div class="gk-section">
      <h2 class="gk-section-title">⚠️ High-Frequency Exam Traps</h2>
      <div class="gk-scroll">
        <table class="gk-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Trap</th><th>Correct Answer</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Who was the first Governor-General of India (not just Bengal)?</td>
              <td><strong>Lord William Bentinck</strong> (1833) — not Warren Hastings, who was G-G of Bengal only</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Sati was abolished under which act and which Governor-General?</td>
              <td><strong>Bengal Sati Regulation XVII, 4 December 1829</strong> under <strong>Lord William Bentinck</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Who was the last Governor-General AND first Viceroy?</td>
              <td><strong>Lord Canning</strong> — the same person held both titles; Govt of India Act 1858 transformed his title</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>INC was founded under which Viceroy?</td>
              <td><strong>Lord Dufferin</strong> (1884–1888) — NOT Lord Ripon (common confusion as Ripon was the "good" Viceroy who came before)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Partition of Bengal (1905) was annulled under whom?</td>
              <td><strong>Lord Hardinge II</strong> in 1911 — NOT under Minto II who was the Viceroy when it was done (by Curzon)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Who introduced separate electorates for Muslims?</td>
              <td><strong>Lord Minto II</strong> via Indian Councils Act 1909 (Morley-Minto Reforms) — NOT Lord Curzon</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Who was the only Viceroy assassinated in India?</td>
              <td><strong>Lord Mayo</strong> (1872) — killed by convict Sher Ali at Port Blair, Andaman Islands</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Who was the last Governor-General of India?</td>
              <td><strong>C. Rajagopalachari</strong> (Rajaji) — not Mountbatten. Mountbatten was first G-G of independent India; Rajaji was last.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Who was the longest-serving Viceroy?</td>
              <td><strong>Lord Linlithgow</strong> (1936–1944) — 8 years. Often confused with Lord Curzon (who served 6 years but is more prominent in UPSC syllabus).</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Gandhi-Irwin Pact was signed in which year?</td>
              <td><strong>5 March 1931</strong> — often confused with 1930 (year of Salt March) or 1932 (Poona Pact year)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Delhi was made capital under which Viceroy?</td>
              <td><strong>Lord Hardinge II</strong> — announced at Delhi Durbar <strong>12 December 1911</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Quit India Movement was launched under which Viceroy?</td>
              <td><strong>Lord Linlithgow</strong> — 8 August 1942. NOT Lord Wavell (who came later)</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="gk-note">
      <strong>Exam strategy:</strong> UPSC tests Viceroys on three axes — (1) which act / reform / event happened under whom (the quick-recall table above), (2) "firsts" and "onlys" (first G-G, first Viceroy, only Indian G-G, only assassinated Viceroy), (3) negative MCQs mixing up adjacent Viceroys (Curzon vs Minto II, Dufferin vs Ripon, Hardinge II vs Chelmsford). The 1833 / 1858 title transitions and the Canning dual-title are the most commonly tested structural facts.
    </div>

